  "review_text": "[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=extralarge; fonttype=bold; text=Decoder Ring]\n\nThe <b>Decoder Ring</b> is Longbox Playback's way of acknowledging something the characters - and the original 1960s reader - <i>could not possibly know</i>, but <b>you</b>, the modern reader, absolutely do.\n\nIt's the place where future continuity, later retcons, creator interviews, and decades-later callbacks get their moment to shine without derailing the main review, all to preserve the \"Scenario.\"\n\nIf the main text is \"reading the issue as it existed in 1961,\" the Decoder Ring adds bits that enhance \"reading it with 60+ years of hindsight.\"\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= What Belongs in a Decoder Ring Note]\n\nA Decoder Ring entry is triggered when the comic contains something that becomes funnier, richer, or more interesting <b>because of what happens later</b>.\n\nSome examples:\n[ASSET: right | TakeYourMoney | width=small] [HANG] * <b>Recurring background characters</b> who unexpectedly return decades later (e.g., the same taxi driver from [LINK:1961:FF_1|FF #1] showing up again in issue <i>#160</i> - a deep cut no 1961 reader could predict)\n[BR]\n[HANG] * <b>Origins or transformations</b> that weren't planned at the time (e.g., Carol Danvers' brush with death in <i>Captain Marvel #18</i> eventually becoming the seed of her Ms. Marvel powers)\n[BR]\n[HANG] * <b>Characters who reappear after geological time gaps</b> (e.g., She-Hulk's 1980s commentary about the Toad Men decades after their one-and-done appearance in <i>[LINK:1962:HULK_2|Hulk #2]</i>)\n[BR]\n[HANG] * <b>Retcons that change how a scene reads</b> (e.g., \"this throwaway panel becomes important 15 years later when...\")\n[BR]\n[HANG] * <b>Continuity echoes</b> that only make sense with a long view (e.g., a minor plot device that becomes a franchise staple)\n\nIf it's the kind of thing you'd lean over and whisper to a friend, \"Okay, this won't matter for 20 years, but <i>trust</i> me, it's hilarious\" ... then it's <i>exactly</i> what belongs in the Decoder Ring.\n\nHowever, while you'll find them used in this archive here and there, they tend to be somewhat sparse in order to help stay grounded in the moment - to stay \"<i>within the Scenario</i>\" as much as possible.\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= Why It Exists]\n\nBecause reading early Marvel with modern knowledge is a unique experience.&nbsp; You're not just reading the story -- you're watching <b>history accidentally happen</b>.\n\nThe Decoder Ring lets you:\n[HANG] * preserve the purity of the original reading (you can ignore them entirely)\n[HANG] * avoid cluttering the main review with continuity digressions\n[HANG] * still celebrate the weird, wonderful long-tail connections that make Marvel history fun\n\nIt's the <b>archivist's wink</b> - a nod to the reader that says, \"I know something Stan and Jack didn't.\"\n\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= How It Works]\n\nDecoder Ring entries appear inline as a small spinning ring, like this:&nbsp; [DECODER_RING: <b>Congratulations!</b>  You found the <i>totally awesome</i> \"future-aware\" insight!]&nbsp; (just hover over it)\n\nEach entry is:\n[HANG] * <b>Brief</b> - one idea, one insight\n[HANG] * <b>Spoil-light</b> - never ruins a plot, only enriches it\n[HANG] * <b>Optional</b> - the review reads cleanly without it\n[DEVNOTE: HANG * <b>Searchable</b> - all entries are stored in metadata for future indexing]\n\nThe main review stays immersive.\n[BR] The Decoder Ring handles the archaeology.\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= Long-Term Vision]\n\n[ASSET: right | ThisIsForReal | width=20%] As the archive grows, the Decoder Ring becomes:\n[BR] [HANG] * a <b>cross-decade continuity atlas</b>\n[BR] [HANG] * a <b>map of callbacks, retcons, and resurrected concepts</b>\n[BR] [HANG] * a <b>living index of Marvel's accidental long game</b>\n[BR]\n[BR] [HANG0] Maybe one day, you'll even be able to browse all Decoder Ring entries in one place - a searchable, filterable treasure trove of \"you'd never know this unless you'd read 40 years of comics.\"\n[BR]\n[BR] [HANG0] [SPAN: severity=warning; fonttype=bold; text=(But... no promises!)]"
}